/-
# `Dregg2.Crypto.MlKemEncapsAcvp` -- the ML-KEM-768 encapsulation KAT floor, anchored to the
**COMPLETE NIST-published ACVP group**.

This module widens the ML-KEM-768 encapsulation anchor from the single vector pinned in
`MlKemEncaps` (`tcId = 26`) to ALL 25 cases of NIST's own AFT group, and proves the Lean
`mlkemEncaps` reproduces NIST's expected ciphertext AND shared secret on every one of them.

## Provenance (exact, verifiable -- nothing here is crate-generated or hand-written)

* Repository: `https://github.com/usnistgov/ACVP-Server` (NIST's own ACVP server / vector
  repository), branch `master`, fetched 2026-07-20 via `raw.githubusercontent.com`.
* File: `gen-val/json-files/ML-KEM-encapDecap-FIPS203/internalProjection.json`
* Downloaded-file digests -- md5 `9e056dac30792a25f0560a359cdc0840`,
  sha256 `f1e22b7d399dde7bf61b838770c658a380e4b1cfc4bd395dbed9ec6c1d977d9d`.
* Group: `tgId = 2` (`testType = "AFT"`, `function = "encapsulation"`,
  `parameterSet = "ML-KEM-768"`) -- the group matching `mlkemEncaps`, which implements FIPS 203
  Algorithm 17 `ML-KEM.Encaps` around Algorithm 14 `K-PKE.Encrypt`.
* Test cases: `tcId` 26-50 -- ALL 25 of the group.

The `ek` / `dk` / `m` / `c` / `k` fields are pinned VERBATIM as the lowercase hex strings appearing
in the ACVP JSON (transcribed programmatically, never retyped). `c` and `k` are NIST's expected
OUTPUTS: no Rust implementation is the specification anchor for this result.

INDEPENDENTLY RE-VERIFIED: the single vector already pinned in `MlKemEncaps` (`tcId = 26`,
`acvpEk`/`acvpDk`/`acvpM`/`acvpCt`/`acvpK`) was re-extracted from this download and matches those
existing byte arrays exactly -- so this file and the pre-existing pin agree on their overlap.

## What this proves, and what it does NOT

`encaps_matches_acvp_group` is a `List.all` over the pinned batch, closed by a single `native_decide`
over the compiled `def`s. It is a KAT -- agreement with NIST on 25 CONCRETE inputs -- NOT a
`forall`-quantified correctness theorem. There is NO `forall` in it. The `forall` obligation
(`mlkemEncaps` refines the FIPS 203 spec for ALL inputs) lives in `EncapsCoreSpec` and remains a
SEPARATE, and still open, statement. Widening the group raises the empirical floor and removes the
"one cherry-picked vector" objection; it does not convert a KAT into a proof.

`native_decide` runs the COMPILED `def`s, so each theorem here carries its per-declaration
compiler-trust axiom `..._native.native_decide.ax` (the v4.30 realization of `Lean.ofReduceBool` /
`Lean.trustCompiler`) -- the same residual `Keccak`, `MlKemRing` and `MlKemCodec` already name.

★ UNDER ALL OF IT: `mlkemEncaps` bottoms out in `Keccak` (SHA3-256/512, SHAKE128/256). Whatever the
assurance status of those Keccak definitions is, THIS FILE INHERITS IT. Agreement with NIST on 25
vectors is evidence that the Keccak defs are the real thing, but it is KAT evidence, not a proof.
-/
import Dregg2.Crypto.AcvpHex
import Dregg2.Crypto.MlKemEncaps

namespace Dregg2.Crypto.MlKemEncapsAcvp

open Dregg2.Crypto.AcvpHex (hexBytes hexOfLen)
open Dregg2.Crypto.MlKemEncaps (mlkemEncaps)
open Dregg2.Crypto.MlKemDecaps (mlkemDecaps)

set_option maxRecDepth 1000000
set_option maxHeartbeats 0

/-- One NIST ACVP `ML-KEM-encapDecap-FIPS203` encapsulation test case, fields verbatim from the
published JSON. `c` and `k` are NIST's expected outputs. -/
structure EncapsVec where
  tcId : Nat
  /-- NIST-supplied encapsulation key. -/
  ek : String
  /-- NIST-supplied decapsulation key (used only by the round-trip theorem). -/
  dk : String
  /-- NIST-supplied encapsulation randomness. -/
  m : String
  /-- NIST's EXPECTED ciphertext. -/
  c : String
  /-- NIST's EXPECTED shared secret. -/
  k : String

/-- `mlkemEncaps` run on one decoded vector reproduces NIST's expected `(c, k)` BYTE-FOR-BYTE. -/
def agreesWithAcvp (v : EncapsVec) : Bool :=
  mlkemEncaps (hexBytes v.ek) (hexBytes v.m) == (hexBytes v.c, hexBytes v.k)

/-- Decaps of NIST's `dk` over the ciphertext Lean just produced recovers NIST's expected `k`. -/
def roundTripsWithAcvp (v : EncapsVec) : Bool :=
  mlkemDecaps (hexBytes v.dk) (mlkemEncaps (hexBytes v.ek) (hexBytes v.m)).1 == hexBytes v.k

/-- Every pinned hex field decodes (even length, all hex) and carries the FIPS 203 ML-KEM-768 size. -/
def wellFormed (v : EncapsVec) : Bool :=
  hexOfLen v.ek 1184 && hexOfLen v.dk 2400 && hexOfLen v.m 32 &&
  hexOfLen v.c 1088 && hexOfLen v.k 32

